= Task 2
== Baseline
To have a comparison for how good the optimization on the problem is, the starter code is tested on a machine, and yields the following loss and test accuracy after 10 epochs:
\
Test set: Average loss: 0.0172,         Accuracy: 5953/10000 (59.5299%)

Throughout the report, the standard for what is a better model will be the accuracy it achieves. A loss is hard to compare to actual performance, and if this was a real world case where a model had to be developed, it would be what was actually important.




== Basic and Batch SGD
The given starter code, it is very easy to modify to accommodate either basic SGD by setting the batch to 1, or to run Batch SGD where the batch size is set to the full training set (60,000). 

=== Batch SGD:
Training with a batch size of 60,000 is a lot more computationally expensive, which is usually leveraged with either parallel processes, or second-order methods. Deep learning is a notorious non-convex problem, so having the possibility to do second-order methods is not guaranteed to decrease the test loss and accuracy. Using batch SGD without changing other parameters leads to the following loss/accuracy after 10 epochs:
\
Test set: Average loss: 0.0002,         Accuracy: 1236/10000 (12.3599%) 

This is however not a good representation for batch training, since the full knowledge of the entire function is not properly utilized. This will be addressed in @second-order-methods. 

=== Basic SGD:
Basic SGD, which uses a batch size of 1, yielded significantly better initial convergence.  This was again simply implemented by modifying the basic code to have a batch size of 1.
\
Test set: Average loss: 0.3060,         Accuracy: 8917/10000 (89.1699%)

This performance can also be explained in the amount of steps, or gradient updates. For 60,000 pictures, with a batch size of one, 10 epochs with basic SGD updates the gradient 600,000 times, wheres Batch SGD only updates 10 times. Basic SGD's drastic increase in performance will theoretically slow down, since it updates on each picture at a time, the amount of noise will make it hard for it converge to an optimum for the entire problem (the 60,000 pictures). 

