Here it was observed that a few different models performed well, and in different areas. Ada and Adam based models converge quicker than less dynamic methods such as classic SGD. However, the more dynamic methods were more prone to overfit on the training data, and thereby lead to a increase in the test loss, and a reduced accuracy. This means that models such as AdamW converge quickly, and with the right regularization and noise techniques, therefore has more time to converge to a better minium. Whereas SGD, that isn't as prone to overfitting, can be trained a lot longer without the risk of overfitting. 

To find the optimal solution, three different paths will be further developed:
- Using AdamW to converge quickly within 10 epochs
- Using AdamW to converge to optimal solution with regularization
- Using SGD to converge to optimal without regularization

Each of the following methods can then be further optimized with their parameters such as learning rate and momentum, but other techniques to reduce noise will also be used. 

