    caption: [Warmup + \ Cosine decay]
  )
), caption: [different learning rates examples @divedeep]
)
While all of the above might work well, after testing, the warm up scheduler shows to outperform the others. Cosine decay might have a generally slower convergence than something simple as a factor decay, since it opts to not drastically decreasing the learning rate at the very start. Instead it "refines" the optimization process later on. The only drawback of this is the initial high learning rate. This can be optimized using the warmup. With warmup the learning rate start out making sure the optimization is on the right path, before encreasing the learning rate and then doing cosine decay. This works really well in many scenarios, as well as this problem. Furthermore, based on prior work, this approach has been found to work reliably. 

