== Second-order Methods <second-order-methods>
Second order methods have the power to leverage a lot more information, typically in the form hessians to use this to converge in a reduced amount of steps (Not necessarily time, since each step is more computationally expensive). To test the viability of second order methods, the quasi-newton method L-BFGS was used to to it's ability to use limited memory, and therefore being possible to run on smaller machines. As well as being a quasi-newton ensures that it doesn't have to compute the exact hessian, but only an approximation. This makes L-BFGS a good suit for this large scale unconstrained optimization problem. 

For this project, L-BFGS was implemented with strong wolfe conditions. Because as a default, L-BFGS, as other second-order methods use a step size of one due to it's nature of finding the optimal direction. By introducing strong wolfe conditions, it ensures that the optimizer doesn't end up overshooting the target, and therefore not being able to "get back" and find the minimum. This occurred during the initial testing phase.

The L-BFGS ended up being quite unreliable, with its range of accuracy after 10 epochs being between 10-88% (usually withing 70-86%), thereby making the optimizer quite vulnerable to the starting conditions.

This vulnerability and unpredictability about whether the model will even converge was the reason for this project that it was not used.

