== Discussion
Although not everything in the project can be exploitively attributed to theory, there is some trends that show up, hinting to the underlying and methods, when and why they should be used.

For finding the optimal fast converging AdamW, we see a trend that points bold strategies. Having the learning rate low is to be expected, as AdamW uses adaptive momentum. By having a lower initial learning rate, it has an easier time fitting to the correct parameters as seen with @AdamW-learning-rate. This same trend can be seen with @AdamW-batch-size. By having the batch size at the lower range with for example 16, it enables it to compute more gradients within the first few epochs, thereby converging quicker. Since it is more stochastic than larger batch sizes, the steps might not be in the most optimal way, but it compensates for that with lots of updates instead. This trend continues for dynamic sampling, where in @dynamic-sampling-fast-adamW a smaller step size (leading to a larger $tau$ value) yields better results. By having the batch size small at the start, it manages to quickly move in the correct direction, and with quickly increasing it to larger batch sizes, it manges to converge more accurately later. This might be why as shown in @simulated_annealing_for_adamW_16, using a learning rate scheduler doesn't have an impressive benefit. The previously mentioned parameters and noise reduction techniques already achieves these goals.

Finding the optimal solution for AdamW was about reusing some elements, and then optimizing for a different objective. Here since the objective was not to converge quickly, different batch sizes could be chosen. As seen in @AdamW-batch-size, a batch size of 256 converges much slower, but performs a lot better at later stages. This also fits with the theory that a larger batch size, will take more precise steps later in the training. Having settled on a batch size of 256, regularization could be tested. Here a relatively large weight decay was found to work better. Afterwards the model could be fine tuned with dynamic sampling and scheduled learning. 


The optimal solution for SGD with momentum was also found by first finding an appropriate learning rate. Here the learning rate $0.001$ found to be most optimal. @sgd_momentum shows a comparison of different momentum values, and its quite clear that momentum plays a significant role. The more momentum, the better the model performs. This could be because the momentum helps the optimizer move in the overall best direction, and doesn't get as easily pulled towards and in local minimums. A general batch was chosen to be able to converge better at later stages. Lower batch sizes might be able to converge quicker, but could struggle to optimize at the later stages due to the limited amount of points it optimizes on. 


=== Batch sizes
Trough this project, it has been observed that the batch size has had a significant effect. Batch optimization might be a lot slower to converge, since it needs to evaluate the entire dataset to take a single step, whereas stochastic variants can perform thousands of gradient updates within a single epoch. The obvious drawback is the amount of noise evaluating on a single data point at time makes it unlikely to converge to a great optimum. A good optimizer utilizes both of these strengths, using a small batch size at the start, and gradually increases towards the end. This is what is seen in the optimal models like AdamW that starts with a relative small batch size, but ends up using the entire dataset. 



=== Possible improvements
If case2 of the project was to be redone, there would be made some changes. Given more time, each run would be made 3 different times, and then the average would be taken. This would reduce a noise factor, that could have contributed to some optimizers/parameters being possibly wrongfully chosen. 
\
The complexity of the problem, made it hard to leverage relevant theory as much as was wanted from the group, but it nonetheless gave valuable experience in how complex optimization problems can be. 



== Conclusion
After deliberate and meticulous optimization trough mainly experimentation, final models was found that satisfied the given requirements and gave a reasonable performance. Models that converged to much better optimums, in significantly shorter time was achieved.




